Not a Chance:<br><br>
The way not to double post is to be very patient after you click that button.  It takes a while, and only one click is enough to make the post ;-)<br><br>
Jed,<br><br>
I'm going to give you some information from my diaries from the 1970's.  It will illuminate a bit of why we felt, and feel, the way we do.<br><br>
November 9, 1970<br><br>
&quot;(One of our members) talked about recondo school and what was taught.  He was told (presumably by Vietnamese) that Americans here live and fight because of their hate for the people.  And the VC recognize this and indoctrinate their people to hate Americans.  THey saf that Americans are here to take their land.  So the people fight Americans.<br><br>
&quot;(One of our members) is also unhappy at the way soldiers are tried for murder for killing women and children.  So's (another of our members).  Many women &amp; children are not innocent, but are killed in self-defense.  When (the other of our members) was in the hospital for shoulder wounds, a Marine was added for shratnal wounds of the legs.  A woman had thrown a granade at him and he had to kill her...&quot;<br><br>
I'm sure that the VC and North Vietnamese did not have trials on this sort of thing.  We did.  That doesn't mean that we were always in the right.  It does mean that we operated under a very different set of rules than did the NVA and the VC.  <br><br>
November 16, 1970<br><br>
&quot;I'm sort of depressed today.  I'm here because I feel I should be; however my nature rebells.  I know I'd be prefectly happy 200 yrs ago in the Oregon wilderness with a bow, my tribe and a wife.  This may be one of my fanticies, however I feel caught up in issues which aren't mine and, while they may be &quot;right&quot; or &quot;a moral obligation,&quot; don't directly affect my family back home, except for my being here.  It seems that the times demand decisions and actions inconsistent with those of another era.  I seem to be living ahead of my times.&quot;<br><br>
We all had doubts and problems with some of the things which were occurring.  The press did not help with their reporting.  I remember getting really mad at Paul Harvey when he reported that our helicopters were made with a skin of magnesium which burned very quickly when they were hit.  In fact, there was one helicopter which was built that way, but it was an old one which was operated by the South Vietnamese some years before.<br><br>
To say that any of us had everything all figured out is probably not true, but neither was it true that we were there solely because of our hate for the Vietnamese people.  The protestors did not have standing with us because we knew of the mis-information that was being delivered, and the obvious hate for us on the part of the protestors at that time.  <br><br>
Jed, concerning the &quot;dog-eat-dog&quot; market philosophy, I prefer it to the &quot;dog-kill-dog&quot; philosophy of the communists.  The former was a response to &quot;supply and demand,&quot; and the &quot;dog-eat-dog&quot; metaphor was just that, a metaphor.  Unfortunately, I cannot say the same for the communist philosophy.  
